  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Royce Lewis Homer Lifts Minnesota Over Houston Astros",
    "subheadline": "MIN 5, HOU 4. The long ball carries MIN.",
    "lead_angle": "Royce Lewis parked a Peter Lambert fastball in the right field seats, a seventh-inning solo shot that stood up as the winner in a 5-4 Minnesota Twins victory over the Houston Astros. The Twins muscled their way to a road win entirely on the strength of the long ball, getting key home runs from Josh Bell and Victor Caratini earlier in the contest. Zebby Matthews earned the win for Minnesota, scattering six hits over six innings. Lambert was saddled with the loss for Houston.\n\nThe Twins built their lead with timely power. Bell cracked a two-run homer in the fourth inning to break a scoreless tie. After the Astros scratched one across against Matthews in the fifth, Victor Caratini answered with a solo blast in the sixth, stretching the lead back to three. The consistent barrage gave Minnesota just enough cushion to withstand a late Houston charge, a three-run ninth-inning rally that fell short when Yoendrys Gómez induced a final groundout.\n\nWhile Houston’s Cam Smith did his best to keep pace with two solo home runs of his own, it was Lewis who provided the pivotal swing. He finished just 1-for-4, but his one hit left the yard and ultimately decided the game. The victory is a crucial one for the Twins, keeping them in the thick of a tight divisional race as the season’s second half looms. It was a needed win on the road against a formidable opponent, a game where every swing mattered.",
    "reason": "A multi-home-run game by a single player gives the day a clear protagonist."
  },
